## The blocking call(s)

Finding **crime_00023** (`sync_io_in_hotpath`) in `src/api/files.ts` pinpoints three synchronous fs calls inside `loadPlanSchema`, each of which blocks the event loop for the duration of the I/O:

> - `` `existsSync` @L12 in `loadPlanSchema` (domain function) ``
> - `` `statSync` @L13 in `loadPlanSchema` (domain function) ``
> - `` `readFileSync` @L15 in `loadPlanSchema` (domain function) ``
> - lines: 12, 13, 15
> - swap for the async variant (`readFile`, `writeFile`, `exec`, …) and `await` it

Under concurrent load every request enters `loadPlanSchema` and pays the cost of three blocking syscalls back-to-back on the main thread — that's where the p99 latency and event-loop lag are coming from. The suggested action is explicit:

> Replace the `*Sync` call with its async counterpart and `await` it. The function may need to be marked `async`…

## Smallest async migration

The three offenders are `fs.existsSync`, `fs.statSync`, `fs.readFileSync`. Swap to `fs/promises` and make the function `async` — the name, parameter list, and the *value* it resolves with all stay the same; only the wrapper changes from `T` to `Promise<T>`:

```ts
import { readFile, stat } from "node:fs/promises";

export async function loadPlanSchema(path: string): Promise<PlanSchema> {
  try {
    const info = await stat(path);              // replaces existsSync + statSync
    if (!info.isFile()) throw new Error(`not a file: ${path}`);
    const raw = await readFile(path, "utf8");   // replaces readFileSync
    return JSON.parse(raw) as PlanSchema;
  } catch (err: any) {
    if (err?.code === "ENOENT") throw new Error(`schema missing: ${path}`);
    throw err;
  }
}
```

Two specific notes on preserving the contract:

1. **Drop `existsSync` entirely.** The classic "exists then read" pattern is a TOCTOU race anyway; let `stat`/`readFile` throw `ENOENT` and handle it in the catch. That keeps behaviour identical for callers (still throws on missing file) without an extra syscall.
2. **Callers must `await`.** Any caller currently doing `const s = loadPlanSchema(p)` becomes `const s = await loadPlanSchema(p)`, and any non-async caller in the request hot path needs to be marked `async`. That propagation *is* the migration — there is no smaller fix that actually frees the event loop. Caching the parsed schema is orthogonal and, per your instruction, not the right lever here.
